        "embed_id": "a366d1bd-50dd-4ebe-9301-910d50854a52",
        "type": "website",
        "content": "type: search_result\ntitle: How to Prepare for a Dermatologist Appointment - Guides\nurl: \"https://www.zocdoc.com/blog/how-to-prepare-for-a-dermatologist-appointment/\"\ndescription: \"Tempting as it may be to bring all your skincare questions to the table, Piliang says to prioritize just one or two concerns during an appointment. If you arrive with a long list of issues — a rash, a skin spot, acne, hair loss — your dermatologist won’t be able to give each one the attention it deserves. “You’ll get each problem addressed with more detail and more care if you have it limited to one or two things,” she said. If you have a laundry list of skin issues, schedule a follow-up appointment to talk through the topics you didn’t have time to discuss in detail.\"\npage_age: \"March 3, 2023\"\nprofile_name: Zocdoc\nmeta_url_favicon: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/JRC5ZSvJVnTvne8X_TeySyojovFZP7YcAAmsqPEjQaE/rs:fit:32:32:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cDovL2Zhdmlj/b25zLnNlYXJjaC5i/cmF2ZS5jb20vaWNv/bnMvZmRjNGUxN2E0/ZjczMzk1YWZjNWY2/N2I3YWFhNWU4OTNi/MGU1ZmMzMzIzOTBm/YzZlZGZmNzQ0MDA4/NjQ0NzdiMy93d3cu/em9jZG9jLmNvbS8\"\nthumbnail_src: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/KqkKGYHmXCvvZJXCkD77gqe6VAnv-5cmLm7DmvF_r7s/rs:fit:200:200:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVw/YXBlcmdvd24ud3Bl/bmdpbmUuY29tL3dw/LWNvbnRlbnQvdXBs/b2Fkcy8yMDE4LzA5/L0Rlcm1hdG9sb2d5/LTAxX0xPLnBuZw\"\nthumbnail_original: \"https://thepapergown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Dermatology-01_LO.png\"\nextra_snippets: \"Tempting as it may be to bring all your skincare questions to the table, Piliang says to prioritize just one or two concerns during an appointment. If you arrive with a long list of issues — a rash, a skin spot, acne, hair loss — your dermatologist won’t be able to give each one the attention it deserves. “You’ll get each problem addressed with more detail and more care if you have it limited to one or two things,” she said. If you have a laundry list of skin issues, schedule a follow-up appointment to talk through the topics you didn’t have time to discuss in detail.|In general, there are two types of dermatology appointments: a consultation and a skin check, also known as a cancer screening. If you’re going in for a consultation on a specific problem like a rash, a medication reaction or a brush with poison ivy, prepare ahead of time by taking inventory of the issue: Make note of when the problem started and take stock of your symptoms.|Seems like a smart idea to make an appointment with a dermatologist before the year ends. https://eastcarolinadermatology.com/greenville ... Thank you for explaining that you should bring a list of your current medications and supplements. I didn’t realize that supplements would be important to bring to the dermatologist. We’ll be sure to keep this in mind when my daughter visits them later this week so that we’re prepared.|But there are steps you should take beforehand to ensure you make the most of your time in the exam room, and some of them (like removing your toenail polish) aren’t so obvious. We talked to Dr. Melissa Piliang, a dermatologist at the Cleveland Clinic, to learn how patients should prepare for different types of dermatology appointments.\"\nhash: a282d378b7871c53\nembed_ref: zocdoc.com-CkO\napp_id: web\nskill_id: search",
